","1140":"1140","1162":"1162","1194":"1194","1238":"1238","1279":"1279","1145":"1145","1211":"1211","1229":"1229","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Anglie","Mulgrave Castle, Yorkshire, England":"Mulgrave Castle, Yorkshire, Anglie","Thurnham, Kent, England":"Thurnham, Kent, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1162–26 April 1211":"omkring 1162–26. april 1211","1162–1211":"1162–1211","1194–1238":"1194–1238","1176–1220":"1176–1220","1229–1279":"1229–1279","1197–1238":"1197–1238","1140–1174":"1140–1174","1145–Female":"1145–Afdød","about 1162":"omkring 1162","26 April 1211":"26. april 1211","1220":"1220","1176":"1176","1197":"1197","1174":"1174","1195":"1195","1140":"1140","1162":"1162","1194":"1194","1238":"1238","1279":"1279","1145":"1145","1211":"1211","1229":"1229","Yorkshire, England":"Jórvík, England","Mulgrave Castle, Yorkshire, England":"Mulgrave Castle, Jórvík, England","Thurnham, Kent, England":"Thurnham, Kent, England"},"nl":{"about 1162–26 April 1211":"circa 1162–26 april 1211","1162–1211":"1162–1211","1194–1238":"1194–1238","1176–1220":"1176–1220","1229–1279":"1229–1279","1197–1238":"1197–1238","1140–1174":"1140–1174","1145–Female":"1145–Overleden","about 1162":"circa 1162","26 April 1211":"26 april 1211","1220":"1220","1176":"1176","1197":"1197","1174":"1174","1195":"1195","1140":"1140","1162":"1162","1194":"1194","1238":"1238","1279":"1279","1145":"1145","1211":"1211","1229":"1229","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Mulgrave Castle, Yorkshire, England":"Mulgrave Castle, Yorkshire, England","Thurnham, Kent, England":"Thurnham, Kent, England"},"en":{"about 1162–26 April 1211":"about 1162–26 April 1211","1162–1211":"1162–1211","1194–1238":"1194–1238","1176–1220":"1176–1220","1229–1279":"1229–1279","1197–1238":"1197–1238","1140–1174":"1140–1174","1145–Female":"1145–Deceased","about 1162":"about 1162","26 April 1211":"26 April 1211","1220":"1220","1176":"1176","1197":"1197","1174":"1174","1195":"1195","1140":"1140","1162":"1162","1194":"1194","1238":"1238","1279":"1279","1145":"1145","1211":"1211","1229":"1229","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Mulgrave Castle, Yorkshire, England":"Mulgrave Castle, Yorkshire, England","Thurnham, Kent, England":"Thurnham, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Turnham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Buckinghamshire and Middlesex): habitational name, primarily from Turnham Green in Chiswick (Greater London), but occasionally also from Turnham Hall in Cliffe (Yorkshire). The placenames probably derive from Old English <i>trun</i>, <i>turn</i> ‘circular, round’, possibly also ‘bend (in a river)’, + <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’ or <i>hamm</i> ‘enclosure, water meadow’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"III","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Japanese Yuko, Aiko, Hideaki, Hiroki, Hiroyuki, Isamu, Kaoru, Katsumi, Keiichiro, Kenji, Masako, Masayuki.","Japanese: variously written, sometimes with characters used phonetically; the most probable meanings are 仁井 ‘benevolent well’, 新居 ‘new residence’, or 新井 ‘new well’. It is not common in Japan."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Turnham III was born about 1162, in Thurnham, Kent, England, his father, Baron Robert de Turnham, was 24 and his mother, Isabel Mulgrave, was 19. He married Isabela de Thornhill in 1195. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 26 April 1211, in Yorkshire, England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"about 1162–26 April 1211":"umbes 1162–26. aprill 1211","1162–1211":"1162–1211","1194–1238":"1194–1238","1176–1220":"1176–1220","1229–1279":"1229–1279","1197–1238":"1197–1238","1140–1174":"1140–1174","1145–Female":"1145–Surnud","about 1162":"umbes 1162","26 April 1211":"26. aprill 1211","1220":"1220","1176":"1176","1197":"1197","1174":"1174","1195":"1195","1140":"1140","1162":"1162","1194":"1194","1238":"1238","1279":"1279","1145":"1145","1211":"1211","1229":"1229","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Mulgrave Castle, Yorkshire, England":"Mulgrave Castle, Yorkshire, England","Thurnham, Kent, England":"Thurnham, Kent, England"},"fi":{"about 1162–26 April 1211":"noin 1162–26. huhtikuuta 1211","1162–1211":"1162–1211","1194–1238":